{"id":"2101.00920","submitter":"Pierfrancesco Urbani","authors":"Pierfrancesco Urbani","title":"Disordered high-dimensional optimal control","comments":"9 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1751-8121/ac0645","report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC cond-mat.dis-nn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Mean field optimal control problems are a class of optimization problems that\narise from optimal control when applied to the many body setting. In the noisy\ncase one has a set of controllable stochastic processes and a cost function\nthat is a functional of their trajectories. The goal of the optimization is to\nminimize this cost over the control variables. Here we consider the case in\nwhich we have $N$ stochastic processes, or agents, with the associated control\nvariables, which interact in a disordered way so that the resulting cost\nfunction is random. The goal is to find the average minimal cost for $N\\to\n\\infty$, when a typical realization of the quenched random interactions is\nconsidered. We introduce a simple model and show how to perform a dimensional\nreduction from the infinite dimensional case to a set of one dimensional\nstochastic partial differential equations of the Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman and\nFokker-Planck type. The statistical properties of the corresponding stochastic\nterms must be computed self-consistently, as we show explicitly.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 4 Jan 2021 12:30:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 26 Apr 2021 16:34:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-11"}
